{
  "doc_id": "6585",
  "text": "Estrogen is an important hormone in humans. Studies have shown that estrogen signaling plays a significant role in the normal and abnormal growth of the prostate gland [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In 1996, the discovery of estrogen receptor beta (ER ) in rats [CITATION_3] and humans [CITATION_4] changed our understanding of the estrogen signaling. The effects of estrogen on target tissues are now known to be mediated by estrogen receptor alpha (ER ) and ER , which are members of the nuclear hormone receptor family and ligand-activated transcription factors. Expression of estrogen receptors has been found in many other tumors such as breast, uterus, ovarian, colon, and prostate and also identified in bladder, lung cancer, and so on [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The human prostate is equipped with a dual system of ERs: ER and ER , and they undergo significant remodeling in the process of prostate cancer (PCa) development and progression [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . ER is expressed at high levels in the normal prostate, mostly localized to both basal and luminal of the normal prostate [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . However, there is growing evidence showing that ER is gradually lost in cancer progression.",
